 Course Description and Prerequisites Course number, title, description CSCE 310 – Database Systems File structures and access methods; database modeling, design, and user interface; components of database management systems; information storage and retrieval, query languages, high-level language interface with database systems
Term Summer 2022 Section 700 Meeting times and location Asynchronous Online: Lecture will be posted in Canvas; the instructor and TA will host a once-a-week live online (optional) Q&amp;A session (see schedules below) Credit Hours 3-credit hour class, overall duration of 5-weeks Expected Workload: For every one credit hour in which you enroll, you need to allocate 2-3 hours outside of lectures
Prerequisites CSCE 221 with a grade of C or better; junior or senior classification
 be able to write SQL commands to create tables and indexes, insert/update/delete data, and query data from a relational DBMS
 be able to program a data-intensive application using DBMS APIs through a course project, to experience the entire database lifecycle from conception, implementation, and validation; and describe the database application development process with specific supporting examples from the project
 develop effective communication techniques to function productively as a team, with people you have not worked with before, who may have diverse backgrounds/working styles
Success is measured by achieving at least a satisfactory average peer feedback
CSCE 310 Syllabus – Summer 2022 – Wade 3 | Page More specifically:  He will demonstrate understanding of data models, you should be able to: o use data modeling tools like Entity-Relationship Diagrams o translate data models into relational table schemas  He will demonstrate understanding of the relational model of data &amp; its use in query languages for databases, you should be able to: o express queries using relational algebra o use relational algebra operators including extended operators under both set and bag semantics o specify appropriate constraints  He will demonstrate understanding of data normalization, you should be able to: o find keys given a set of functional dependencies o identify tables that are not normalized o decompose unnormalized tables into 4NF, BCNF, and/or 3NF compliant tables  He will demonstrate understanding of views, triggers, and indexes, you should be able to: o define and use views o define and use triggers o decide what indexes to create for a given workload  He will demonstrate proficiency in SQL, you should be able to: o create tables using SQL DDL o specify primary key and foreign key constraints in CREATE TABLE statements o write single block SQL queries o compose SQL queries using set (and bag) operators o write SQL queries with correlated subqueries o write SQL aggregation queries involving GROUP BY and HAVING clauses o translate a user requirement written in English to SQL  He will demonstrate understanding of multi-tier database applications, you should be able to: o design, develop and evaluate a DBMS-backed application to address a problem, using a language of your choice (e.g.
